textDisplay:
The reason that cornflakes create a much crispier texture than flour is that breaking them down by hand creates an uneven texture. Uniformity is the enemy in this application. This is why you’ll increasingly see fried chicken recipes that call for adding the marinade and/or liquid dredge into the flour dredge.

In our restaurant we use a ratio of corn starch and sweet potato starch because the sweet potato starch is very textured and remains so through a great deal of dredging.

It might seem counterintuitive at first, you might balk at the idea of adding liquid to a dry flour dredge, but frying is a process of dehydration so the more you exploit that process to your favor the crispier and crunchier the end result. Think of tempura. A wet dredge leads to a crunchier texture than any dry flour dredge ever could hope to and it’s, when done correctly, thinner than any dry flour dredge.

Not that anyone asked or anything…
